365":"1331–1365","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1350–1438":"1350–1438","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1301–Female":"1301–Deceased","before 1345":"before 1345","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","August 1365":"August 1365","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1331":"1331","about 1350":"about 1350","1328":"1328","1438":"1438","Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England","Branthwaite, Cumberland, England":"Branthwaite, Cumberland, England","Newton Tony, Wiltshire, England":"Newton Tony, Wiltshire, England","Great Orton, Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dyneley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Dineley in Cliviger (Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Dinley","meanings":["English:  See  Dineley  ."]},{"name":"Dinely","meanings":["English:  See  Dineley  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":60,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Dyneley was born in 1322, in Newton Tony, Wiltshire, England, her father, William Dyneley, was 22 and her mother, Mrs. William Dyneley, was 21. She married Thomas de Skelton about 1350, in Great Orton, Cumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1382, in Great Orton, Cumberland, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1322–1382":"1322–1382","1331–1365":"1331–1365","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1350–1438":"1350–1438","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1301–Female":"1301–Surnud","before 1345":"enne 1345","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","August 1365":"august 1365","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1331":"1331","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1328":"1328","1438":"1438","Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England","Branthwaite, Cumberland, England":"Branthwaite, Cumberland, England","Newton Tony, Wiltshire, England":"Newton Tony, Wiltshire, England","Great Orton, Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"1322–1382":"1322–1382","1331–1365":"1331–1365","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1350–1438":"1350–1438","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1301–Female":"1301–Kuollut","before 1345":"ennen vuotta 1345","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","August 1365":"elokuu 1365","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1331":"1331","about 1350":"noin 1350","1328":"1328","1438":"1438","Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Gr